}s:7:"content";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9653:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S_F6iXdleeI/AAAAAAAAADg/Dtl0EEPTsJk/s1600/spock_tpau.jpg"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 360px; height: 240px;" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S_F6iXdleeI/AAAAAAAAADg/Dtl0EEPTsJk/s400/spock_tpau.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5472289753064110562" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="mso-bidi-mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;font-family:Calibri;color:#333333;"><br /></span></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Last night we were watching the PBS special </span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FF6666;">“</span><a href="http://www.pbs.org/thisemotionallife/"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FF6666;">This Emotional Life</span></a><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FF6666;">,” </span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">a fascinating look at the biological and social aspects of human relationships.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">The first episode looks at parent/child bonding, friendship, bullying, and marriage.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Romance and marriage:</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">I try to pretend that cultural differences don’t matter within OUR marriage.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">I want to believe that what matters is that we fell in love with each other, but I sometimes feel like I’ve landed on the planet Vulcan.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">No, seriously, sometimes I can’t help but visualize my mother-in-law as the Vulcan lady with the Yiddish accent asking Spock if Vulcan ceremonies are for “out-verlders.”</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">After watching the program, which featured several American families and their emotional interactions, I asked my husband if his mother, or another Indian of his mother’s generation, watched the episode, would she find it totally alien?</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">The answer:</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">an immediate, emphatic, unequivocal “yes.”</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">The families and couples profiled in the documentary were trying to resolve interpersonal conflicts, trying to restore the romance in their relationships, and working to improve their own sense of fulfillment as well as working towards making their partners fulfilled and happy.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">The couples wanted to improve their communication skills as well as their sex lives.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">But for my mother-in-law, as well as for my husband’s aunts, and even some of his cousins, that view would be completely alien, even contradictory to what they have been taught.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">And as we talked more, I started to wonder if we have a cavernous divide between our ideas of marriage.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"> </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Obviously, not everyone’s family is the same, and if you or your partner come from a particularly wealthy or highly educated family, this might not be true for your situation.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">My husband’s family, however, is extremely middle class—the group that adheres most closely to the social mores or any culture.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Maybe your partner grew up in a household in which the husband and wife were equal and spoke to each other affectionately at home.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">When asked if his parents had an affectionate relationship or treated each other as equals, my husband says that his parents simply put up with one another and got used to one another.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">For them, marriage was about clearly defined roles, familial obligation, and continuity.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">If one were to ask my mother-in-law if she was happy in her marriage, she wouldn’t even understand where that question was coming from.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Her marriage was not about being the wife of a specific person; it was about being a wife in a very general sense—fulfilling a role and a duty.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">As someone who grew up looking to be seen as an individual and loved as an individual, this idea of rigid, clearly-defined roles has been very painful for me (the part that goes like this:</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">hi, we just met and I don’t know you or anything about you, but I’ve decided that you are going to act like this and what relationship we’re going to have, and no, you don’t have say in this, so bend over and touch my feet), but perhaps I will write about that later.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">We really do learn our ideas about marriage, love, and romance from what we see as children, so I’m stuck wondering how this has affected our marriage.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Even if my husband knows something intellectually, what he saw as a child has probably been behind many of our fights and resentments.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Things I see as major problems in a marriage don’t seem like major problems to him.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">I wonder if we hurt each other because, at the end of the day, we’ve internalized different ideas of what marriage is all about.</span><span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-121692389134435022?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"html";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:4:{s:3:"rel";s:7:"replies";s:4:"type";s:20:"application/atom+xml";s:4:"href";s:78:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/feeds/1216923891344350