r="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8nf6mFsUxI/AAAAAAAAACo/MNsdyrY9oCY/s1600/DSC_0027.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8nf6mFsUxI/AAAAAAAAACo/MNsdyrY9oCY/s400/DSC_0027.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5461142220913267474" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal">“Do not marry a Muslim.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Do not marry a Christian.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Do not marry someone who is not from Maharashtra.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>And do not marry a non-vegetarian.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Those are the guidelines my husband’s aunts gave him for finding a wife.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Well, I’m not from Maharashtra, and I am a Christian, but, hey, I happen to be a non-Muslim who is also a vegetarian.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in">“Are you an Indian vegetarian or an American vegetarian?” the forty-something Gujurati man asked me from across the table.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I had just met this guy and he seemed uncomfortable with me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I searched my brain’s data files for information on vegetarianism in each of the two countries.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I knew that some Hindus choose not to eat mushrooms, and I knew that Jains traditionally do not eat vegetables grown underground.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In terms of the US, was he talking about vegans, perhaps?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>People all over the world can be very defensive about eating habits (i.e. Thanksgiving at my grandparents’ house:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Hey kid, you enjoying yer damn rabbit food?” and don’t get me started on the perils of having to answer the “So, why are you a vegetarian?” question—ugh, that’s a different post), so I tried not to sound combative when I asked “What’s an ‘American vegetarian?’”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“An American vegetarian,” he informed me with great authority, “eats chicken and fish.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Unsure where he got his information, I made a quizzical face. “That’s not a vegetarian,” I said.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“That’s someone who is lying of delusional,” I laughed.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Luckily, putting some humor into the situation defused any awkwardness. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>“I’m an ovo-lacto vegetarian,” I explained.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“That’s the most common type here.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I eat eggs and milk—animal products that don’t require killing an animal--but there are also vegetarians here who do not eat dairy, eggs, or honey.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>People all over the world define the term ‘vegetarian’ differently.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In some Indian households, eggs are taboo (explanation:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“eggs are not a vegetable”—very true!).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>But in other households, especially in coastal areas, fish are considered vegetarian.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve even heard an old south Indian auntie call fish “fruit from the sea.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>This is very similar to the old “fish on Fridays” tradition in Christianity.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>As far as I can tell, finding a strict definition of “Indian vegetarian” is just as impossible as finding a definition of an “American vegetarian.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Take a look at Sathya Srinavasan’s <a href="http://cssathya.blogspot.com/2010/03/what-indian-vegetarian-are-you.html">chart</a> (which is a bit tongue in cheek, considering that it includes cannibals) for more definitions of vegetarianism in India.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>My husband, who is a Hindu, started eating meat (chicken and fish) as an adult.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I stopped eating meat as a teenager.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Indians, both here and in India, are often extremely surprised to find out that I am a vegetarian, and often probe me with skeptical questions to try to see if I am actually a vegetarian.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When they find out that I am they are even more shocked.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Some people even seem to refuse to believe it no matter how many times they see me eat.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>For example, once when I was mixing up a batch of falafel, my mother in law came and asked my husband if I was making chicken.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Doesn’t she believe that I’m a vegetarian?” I asked my husband.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Well, you know.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>This has happened more than once, to my chagrin.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>On the other hand, some Hindus consider me, and my mother-in-law, non-veg because we both eat eggs.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>While on the elderly Maharashtrian ladies tour of the Andaman Islands, one older auntie found it necessary to make disparaging remarks about our eating “non-veg” omelets from the buffet table.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>After she complained to the tour guide, those of us who ate eggs were relegated to a separate table. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Those of us at the egg eaters were able to bond a little over being singled out as somehow unclean.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Still, being a vegetarian (well, some people’s idea of a vegetarian!) has helped me to get some older Indians to soften to me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When they learn that I, the foreigner, do something that even many Marathi “manoos” don’t do, they can start to see me less in terms of stereotypes about the west and more in terms of being an individual who has thought through her own choices. </p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-1451188426168813396?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"html";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:4:{s:3:"rel";s:7:"replies";s:4:"type";s:20:"application/atom+xml";s:4:"href";s:79:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/feeds/1451188426168813396/comments/default";s:5:"title";s:13:"Post Comments";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:4:{s:3:"rel";s:7:"replies";s:4:"type";s:9:"text/html";s:4:"href";s:84:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/what-youre-vegetarian.html#comment-form";s:5:"title";s:11:"14 Comments";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"rel";s:4:"edit";s:4:"type";s:20:"application/atom+xml";s:4:"href";s:82:"http://www.blogger.com/feeds/7407232695424203415/po