t";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:8:{s:2:"id";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-6987574907137213818";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:9:"published";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-08T14:35:00.000-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-15T11:39:19.207-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:2:{s:6:"scheme";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";s:4:"term";s:4:"food";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"Some Thoughts on Food-Part Two:  “Madam Doesn’t Want That”";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"text";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"content";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3734:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79DERvyADI/AAAAAAAAACA/wX2WeLcxV9Q/s1600/DSC_9962.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79DERvyADI/AAAAAAAAACA/wX2WeLcxV9Q/s400/DSC_9962.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5458155014158680114" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1"> </span>I’ve always liked spicy food. Even as a child, I kept a bottle of Mexican hot sauce in the fridge for my personal use.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Therefore, the following exchanges annoy the hell out of me:</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">A)</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">ME:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ll get the chili noodles with paneer</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">INDIAN WAITER:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Madam doesn’t want that, it is spicy. [in India you are madam, no matter your age.  This takes a while to get used to]</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">ME:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Madam does want that.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That is why she ordered it.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">B)</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">DESI AUNTIE:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I made it not spicy because we have a non-Indian here (looking at me as though my non-desiness is a communicable disease)</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">MY HUSBAND:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That’s too bad, because she eats spicier food than I do.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">Like the GoriWife pointed out in her most recent post, no matter how often you make desi food, you will hear the following comment and question far too often: “Wow, YOU made this?” (as though only people with Indian ancestry could ever conceivably follow a recipe).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Honestly, I’ve been cooking Indian food since about seventh grade when my family ate an Indian buffet on a trip to Iowa City, Iowa.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I checked out Ismail Merchant’s “<a href="http://www.amazon.com/Ismail-Merchants-Passionate-Meals-Adventurous/dp/0452282322">Passionate Meals</a>” from the local library and started making all kinds of stuff.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I learned to separate ghee from the milk solids in butter, to make my own paneer, make my own yogurt, and roast cardamom pods in the oven on a cookie sheet.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I don’t do that stuff very often any more (I’m usually on a diet), but I do know how to do it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>So do many of my American friends.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>We own cook books.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>No matter how many times I go to India, cook Indian food, shop at the Indian store, or go to Hindi class, every time I sit down at a table in an Indian household or sit down at an Indian restaurant, Indian husband in tow, I will have to deal with people’s strange assumptions about what I eat, what I cook, and what I know.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I will deal with the strange moment of condescension as they tell me what I will and won’t like, and then I’ll eat what I like.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-6987574907137213818?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"html";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:4:{s:3:"rel";s:7:"replies";s:4:"type";s:20:"application/atom+xml";s:4:"href";s:79:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/feeds/6987574907137213818/comments/default";s:5:"title";s:13:"Post Comments";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:4:{s:3:"rel";s:7:"replies";s:4:"type";s:9:"text/html";s:4:"href";s:99:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/some-thoughts-on-food-part-two-madam.html#comment-form";s:5:"title";s:11:"11 Comments";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"rel";s:4:"edit";s:4:"type";s:20:"application/atom+xml";s:4:"href";s:82:"http://www.blogger.com/feeds/7407232695424203415/posts/default/6987574907137213818";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1: