"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:9:"published";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-06T14:22:00.000-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-09T08:04:56.265-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:2:{s:6:"scheme";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";s:4:"term";s:11:"forgiveness";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:2:{s:6:"scheme";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";s:4:"term";s:14:"mother-in-laws";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:2:{s:6:"scheme";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";s:4:"term";s:8:"marriage";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:100:"Forgiveness, Mother-in-Laws, and Hanging on to Yourself in a Marriage (The First of Many Such Posts)";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"text";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"content";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10009:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79CA2FJSgI/AAAAAAAAABw/5IwKGvGqWkI/s1600/DSC_9969.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79CA2FJSgI/AAAAAAAAABw/5IwKGvGqWkI/s400/DSC_9969.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5458153855680858626" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal">Last month, I spent about five days hanging around in an Indian hospital room.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>For most part, it was an exercise is boredom.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My mother-in-law had gone in for some routine surgery, and due to the way Indian hospitals work, she could not be left alone for any period of time.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>For the first time since I have known her, my mother-in-law was feeling vulnerable.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She was not in charge or in control, and she was too drugged-up to care. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>For two of those days, sitting around on a plastic chair, blowing my nose, trying to pay attention to novel, crossing and uncrossing my legs, I did not mind my mother-in-law.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Then, after she started to feel better, she was yelling at members of the hospital staff, ordering the nurses around, and arguing with my husband about details too petty for most of us to even notice.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She was back, and I wanted to be far away from her again.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Indian mother-in-laws have a reputation to uphold.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>If you’ve seen the sketch from “Goodness Gracious Me” about the two Indian mothers trying to one-up each other about how dependant their adult sons are on them, you know what I’m talking about.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Yes, I’m sure there are Indian mother-in-laws out there who are perfectly nice people who treat their sons and their sons’ wives like independent adults, but I do not have one of them.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’m sure I’ll write more about this in later posts, but to put it succinctly, my MIL rejected me before she even met me, and it hurt.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I’ve tried to imagine myself into her shoes.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She is more than forty years my senior.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She does not speak English.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She had never even had a conversation with a white person before she met me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She does not know any Christians.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She had an arranged marriage.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Her parents had an arranged marriage.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My husband is her only son and, though she doesn’t come out and say it, she expected him to marry a nice Maharashtrian Brahmin, probably from the same town.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>This woman, the dream daughter-in-law, would move into her apartment, have some good, obedient, Hindu children, and would take care of her in her old age.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When my husband decided to go to the US to get his master’s degree, she probably imagined he would come back.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>So when I came on the scene, my MIL was not happy.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In her eyes, I took away her son and her chance at living out her old age the way she had planned.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In my defense, I have to ask, since when do we get exactly what we planned for?</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>In her defense, I know that certain members of my husband’s extended family, particularly on his father’s side, have blamed my mother-in-law for raising a bad and rebellious son.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>They look down their noses at her for “letting” her adult son make his own choice in matrimony.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>At family functions, when she sees my husband’s cousins sitting with their Indian spouses, she feels inadequate.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’m sure she feels some satisfaction in having a highly educated daughter-in-law, but at the end of the day, what she got (me) was not what she wanted.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><br /></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Perhaps now is not the time to go into the tale of how she rejected me, but I will say that it involved screaming.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The hurt I feel from her rejection still stings, and still colors every interaction I have with her, and is the cause of more than half the fights my husband and I have.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Before our most recent visit to India, which lasted from mid-February to late March of this year, I worried myself into a daze about how I would respond to my mother-in-law, her outbursts, and her control issues.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I decided that all I wanted was to be able to forgive her and move on, but I’m not sure that I was ready.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>You see, I am not very good at forgiveness.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My memory doesn’t let me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I remember things too clearly—incidents come back at me with the full visceral force of sound, color, smell, pain, and emotion, often when I don’t want them to come back.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When I remember something, I often have to feel all the emotion of that event all over again.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It’s extremely inconvenient, and something I talk to a therapist about.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When I think of my mother-in-law, all the ways she has hurt me and all the ways she COULD hurt me in the future come at me full force.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When I think about her role in my life, I am overcome by anger, resentment, and fear.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She has rejected me, criticized me, and tried to control me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She has physically slapped me more than once, and she has used passive aggressive behavior against me and my husband.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Not only has she never apologized for her behavior or her outbursts, it will probably never occur to her that her behavior has been inappropriate. Yes, I have reason to be angry, but I anger is exhausting.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I want to move on.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I’ve been reading books about forgiveness.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve been amazed at the power of forgiveness and at what some people have been able to forgive.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Still, no matter how often I say, “I want to forgive her,” or “I forgive her,” that doesn’t mean that have forgiven her, or even that I am ready to forgive.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>For a long time, I have used my anger and opposition to my MIL as a way of defining myself within my marriage.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve resented every lump said transferred into her bank account.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve resented all the guilt, stress, and grief she has given my unfortunate spouse.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She was my nemesis:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>the woman who wanted my marriage to fail, the woman who rejected all my beliefs, who looked down her nose at me, my family, and everything I wanted in life.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’m older now, and a little more secure in who I am.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I find myself asking the following questions:</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">-How do I forgive someone who is not sorry for what she has done or does not recognize that she has hurt others?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Obviously, forgiveness is not about standing above the other person and saying “You were wrong,” but I do want to have a real relationship with this woman some day.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>If she never sees how her behavior created the mistrust in our relationship, will our relationship ever improve?</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">-How do I forgive the past when I know that I can, and probably will, be hurt by her again?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Can I forgive the past and still take measures to protect myself in the future?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Does that mean that I have not truly forgiven her?</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">-How much is too much?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>At what point does forgiving someone mean compromising your own integrity?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I don’t have the answers to these questions, but I want to let go of all the anger and fear.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I want to stop letting the past hurt me, but the truth is, I have a lot of fear about the future.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-2850958892951329799?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"html";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:4:{s:3:"rel";s:7:"replies";s:4:"type";s:20:"application/atom+xml";s:4:"href";s:79:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/feeds/2850958892951329799/comments/default";s:5:"title";s:13:"Post Comments";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:4:{s:3:"rel";s:7:"replies";s:4:"type";s:9:"text/html";s:4:"href";s:101:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspo